AGI - Still tensions in American universities after police officers across the country, from New York to Los Angeles, entered into action on campuses where pro-Palestinian demonstrators erected camps and seized academic buildings. The mayor of New York, Eric Adams said that about 300 protesters were arrested on Tuesday night at City College in New York and Columbia University, where anti-Suppressed agents cleared a building that had been occupied for almost a day> to protest against the war of Israel in the Gaza Strip. According to police 173 people were arrested at City College and 109 at Columbia, although it is still unclear how many of the arrested were students and how many came from outside universities and were not admitted on campus, but the same sources said the protest movement was led by "outside agitators", writes the New York Times.
&nbsp;
At the University of California, in Los Angeles, the police intervened before dawn to sedate violent clashes between pro-Palestinian and counter-manifestant protesters, a few hours after the administrators declared an illegal camp on campus. The video footage of the clash showed the counter-manifestants using sticks to attack an improvised barricade surrounding the pro-Palestinian protesters. At least one firework was launched in the camp. At Tulane University in New Orleans, 14 people were arrested at the University of Arizona, campus police used waterers with chemicals to disperse an event, according to Arizona Daily Star.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Columbia campus has been closed to everyone except students living there and employees providing essential services. The rector of the university, Nemat Shafik, asked the NYPD to maintain a presence on site at least until 17 May. Yesterday, Portland State University officials in Oregon urged protesters to leave the library they had occupied on campus. The police also entered a camp at the North Carolina University in Chapel Hill, arresting about 30 people, but protesters returned to occupy after the eviction.
&nbsp;
The NYT reports 'enhancing signs' of tension on some campuses: in Rhode Island, Brown University students dismantled their encampment, while on the west coast, police put an end to employment for eight days of an administrative building at the California State Polytechnic University in Humboldt. According to a New York Times count, more than 1,000 protesters were taken into custody on U.S. campuses from the first raid at Columbia on 18 April.
