&nbsp;
Auster turned off in his house in Brooklyn for complications of lung cancer. Protagonist of American postmodernist literature along with his friends Thomas Pynchon and Don DeLillo, he was able to tell solitudes, anguishes and neuroses of today's man, in search of the identity and meaning of his existence.
&nbsp;
After studying at Columbia University in 1970, Auster traveled to Paris where he worked as a translator until he returned to New York in 1974. The literary debut was the poems and stories published on the 'New York Review of Books' and the 'Harper's Saturday Review'. Then came the novels, 'The country of the last things' (1988), 'The palace of the moon' (1989), 'The music of the case' (1991, from which Philip Haas drew a film in 1993), 'Leviatano' (1992), 'Mr. Vertigo' (1994) and 'Timbuctu' (1998).
